Fletcher and Fortin, Chapter 6

Varied Thrush Example Walkthrough

1 Introduction and Overview

This is a walkthroug of a spatial analysis workflow, based of section 6.3.3: Models that Ignore Spatial Dependence in

Fletcher, Robert; Fortin, Marie-Jose. Spatial Ecology and Conservation Modeling

I use data and modelling ideas from their text, with additional explanations and

  • This walkthrough uses the Simple Features ecosystem of R spatial tools in this walkthrough.
  • This walkthrough uses the ggplot plotting methods, for the most part.
  • This walkthrough uses pipe operator %>% when appropriate:
    • I like to keep the envirnoment free of intermediate variables.
    • Pipes arent always the best option, but they can make compace and elegant code.
    • Here is some info on from the University of Chicago

1.1 The data

Surveys for the varied thrush: Ixoreus naevius

  • Sampling scheme:
  • ~3km transects
  • point surveys - 100m radius
  • 10 pts/transect

1.2 Errata

There are a number of errata in the code provided by the authors, both in the main text and the supplemental code. Ill attempt to point out where I found issues and offer my corrections.

1.2.1 general

  • The authors elevation raster files dont include projection information.
  • The code in the text doesnt include projection info.
  • The projection specification is found in the supplemental code.

1.2.2 correlogram function

There is a mistake in the definition of the moran.results data frame:

They define two columns called null.lower, however one of them should have been null.upper

2.2 Elevation data

Read in the elevation using raster()

crs_dat = "+proj=aea +lat_1=46 +lat_2=48 +lat_0=44 +lon_0=-109.5 +x_0=600000 +y_0=0 +ellps=GRS80 +datum=NAD83 +units=m +no_defs"
dem = raster(file.path(book_data, "elev"))
proj4string(dem) = crs_dat
dem[] = dem[] * 1000

2.3 Build terrain covariates

You can use terrain_brick() from package raster to calculate slope and aspect.

terrain_brick = brick(dem, terrain(dem, opt = c("slope", "aspect"), unit = "radians"))

# brick appends '_km' to the elevetaion layer name:
names(terrain_brick)
## [1] "elev_km" "slope"   "aspect"
# change the name back to 'elevation'
names(terrain_brick)[1] = "elevation"

2.4 Varied Thrush Data

First read the data into a data frame, then make a spatial object:

thrush_df = read.csv(file.path(book_data, "vath_2004.csv"), header = TRUE)

2.4.1 sf version

  • You can make a sf object from a Spatial, data.frame, or data.table object with st_as_sf()
thrush_df = read.csv(file.path(book_data, "vath_2004.csv"), header = TRUE)
thrush_sf = st_as_sf(
  thrush_df,
  coords = c("NORTHING", "EASTING"), 
  crs = crs_dat)

2.4.2 SpatialPointsDataFrame version

  • Raster works better with Spatial objects than sf objects, so Ill proceed with the SPDF version.
thrush_df = read.csv(file.path(book_data, "vath_2004.csv"), header = TRUE)
# There are at least two ways to build a spatialpointsdataframe from a dataframe

# in one line of code:
thrush_spdf = 
  SpatialPointsDataFrame(
    coords = thrush_df[, c("EASTING", "NORTHING")],
    data = thrush_df,
    proj4string = CRS(crs_dat)
  )

# Using coordinates()
thrush_spdf = thrush_df
coordinates(thrush_spdf) = ~ EASTING + NORTHING
proj4string(thrush_spdf) = crs_dat

2.4.3 Extract terrain

  • I have been unsuccessful at finding a quick way to extract values from a stars object given point coordinates.
    • This code uses extract() on the RasterBrick version of the data to add terrain info to the thrush data.
thrush_spdf = cbind(thrush_spdf, extract(terrain_brick, thrush_spdf))
  • The rest of the code works better with an sf object:
thrush_sf = st_as_sf(thrush_spdf)

2.4.4 Center data

The authors centered and scaled, i.e.a z-transfomation, for the modeling. The resulting centered/scaled variables have mean 0 and variance 1.

thrush_sf$elevation_cen = scale(thrush_sf$elevation, center = T, scale = T)
thrush_sf$slope_cen = scale(thrush_sf$slope, center = T, scale = T)
thrush_sf$aspect_cen = scale(thrush_sf$aspect, center = T, scale = T)

3.1 Plot params

Crate ggplot objects for building the plots later.

{
  # Thrush data histogram params
  hist_col = "black"
  hist_fill = "steelblue"
  hist_fill_2 = rgb(0, 0.6, 0.9)
  hist_alpha = 0.2
  
  
  elev_tmp = terrain_brick$elevation
  rng = range(elev_tmp[elev_tmp[] > 0], na.rm = T)
  
  gm_hist_1 = 
    geom_histogram(binwidth = 1, color = hist_col, fill = hist_fill, alpha = hist_alpha)
  gm_thrush_hist_1 =
    geom_histogram(bins = 30, color = hist_col, fill = hist_fill, alpha = hist_alpha)
  gm_thrush_hist_2 =
    geom_histogram(bins = 30, color = hist_col, fill = hist_fill_2, alpha = hist_alpha)
  gm_thrush_hist_3 =
    geom_histogram(bins = 18, color = hist_col, fill = hist_fill_2, alpha = hist_alpha)
  
  # Map color and legend params
  legend_width = 0.4
  
  map_cb =
    guide_colorbar(
      title.position = "left",
      barwidth = unit(legend_width, "npc"))
  
  gg_thrush_start = 0.1
  
  gg_thrush_elevation = 
    scale_fill_gradientn(
      colours = gray.colors(3, start = gg_thrush_start),
      na.value = "transparent",
      guide = map_cb,
      limits = c(rng[1], rng[2])
    )
  
  gg_map_vir = 
    scale_fill_viridis(
      na.value = "transparent",
      guide = map_cb)
  
  gg_map_grayscale = 
    scale_fill_gradientn(
      colours = gray.colors(3),
      na.value = "transparent",
      guide = map_cb)
  
  gg_map_terr = 
    scale_fill_gradientn(
      colours = terrain.colors(20),
      na.value = "transparent",
      guide = map_cb)
  
  gg_map_heat = 
    scale_fill_gradientn(
      colours = heat.colors(3),
      na.value = "transparent",
      guide = map_cb)
  
  gg_map = ggplot() +
    coord_equal() +
    scale_x_discrete(expand=c(0,0)) +
    scale_y_discrete(expand=c(0,0)) +
    theme_map() +
    theme(
      legend.position = "bottom", 
      legend.direction = "horizontal",
      axis.title = element_blank())
  
  rm(rng, elev_tmp)
}

3.8 Correlogram Plots

4 Custom Functions

Functions for creating and plotting correlograms

4.1 Correlogram functions

This is my version of the authors function for calculating a correlogram.

Note that there is a mistake in the definition of the moran.results data frame.

They define two columns called null.lower, however one of them should have been null.upper

plot_ff_correlogram = function(
  corr_1,
  x_lab = "Distance Class",
  y_lab = "Moran's I",
  title = " ")
{
  dat_env = with(
    corr_1, 
    data.frame(
      x = c(dist_class, rev(dist_class)), 
      y = c(null_I_lower, rev(null_I_upper))))
  
  ggplot(corr_1, aes(x = dist_class, y = model_I)) +
    geom_line() +
    geom_hline(yintercept = 0, lty = 2) +
    geom_line(aes(y = null_I_lower), col = gray(0, 0.3)) +
    geom_line(aes(y = null_I_upper), col = gray(0, 0.3)) +
    geom_polygon(aes(x, y), data = dat_env, fill = gray(0, 0.1)) +
    xlab(x_lab) +
    ylab(y_lab) +
    ggtitle(title)
}

4.2 Plot correlogram

Theres also a convenience function for plotting the resulting correlogram. 
ff_correlogram <- function(
  point_coords, 
  point_data,
  max_dist = NULL,
  bin_size = NULL,
  n_sims = 100,
  alpha = 0.05,
  wt_style = "B",
  alternative = "greater")
{
  # package 'spdep' needed for dnearneigh() function.
  # Check whether it is installed:
  stopifnot(require(spdep))
  stopifnot(require(raster))
  
  # If no max distance is provided, calculate 1/3 of the maximum
  # distance between corners of the bounding box
  if (is.null(max_dist))
  {
    # Euclidean distance betwen opposite corners of bounding box
    ext_coords = unlist(raster::extent(SpatialPoints(point_coords)))[1:4]
    max_dist = sqrt(diff(ext_coords[1:2])^2 + diff(ext_coords[3:4])^2) / 3
  }
  
  # If no bin size is provided, create distance classes for 20 bins:
  if (is.null(bin_size)) bin_size = max_dist / 20
  
  # Set up the distance bins
  dist_bins <- seq(0, max_dist, by = bin_size)
  n_bins <- length(dist_bins) - 1
  
  # container for results
  moran_out <- data.frame(
    dist_class =  rep(NA, n_bins),
    model_I = NA,
    model_p = NA,
    null_I_lower = NA, 
    null_I_upper = NA)
  
  for (i in 1:n_bins)
  {
    d_lower <- dist_bins[i] 
    d_upper <- dist_bins[i+1]
    dist_class = mean(d_lower, d_upper)
    
    neigh = 
      spdep::dnearneigh(
        x = point_coords,
        d1 = d_lower,
        d2 = d_upper, 
        longlat = F)
    
    wts = 
      nb2listw(
        neighbours = neigh, 
        style = wt_style, 
        zero.policy = T)
    
    # note alternative is for P-value, 
    # so only 'significant if positive autocorrelation
    mor.i = 
      moran.mc(
        x = point_data, 
        listw = wts, 
        nsim = n_sims, 
        alternative = alternative, 
        zero.policy = T) 
    
    mor.i$data.name
    
    # null envelope 
    null_env = quantile(
      mor.i$res, 
      probs = c(alpha / 2, 1 - alpha / 2), 
      na.rm = T)
    
    moran_out[i, ] = 
      c(
        dist_class = dist_class,
        model_I = mor.i$statistic,
        model_p = mor.i$p.value,
        null_env
      )
  }
  return(moran_out)
}

8 Aspatial Model Diagnostics

In this example, Im including only some very basice model diagnostics: residual plots. Im also going to proceed as if the diagnostics were totally fine. In a real analysis, youd want to perform a more thorough set of model diagnostics.

Heres a very nice article about plotting residuals with ggplot: Visualising Residuals by Simon Jackson

The following are simple base R plots:

8.1 Elevation Model

Elevation vs residuals and predicted vs.residuals plots for model 1:

{
  dat_fit_1 = data.frame(thrush_sf)
  dat_fit_1$predicted = predict(fit_elev_cen, type="response")
  dat_fit_1$residuals = residuals(fit_elev_cen, type="response")
  
  # plot residuals against elevation (the predictor)
  plot(residuals ~ elevation, data = dat_fit_1) 
  
  # Plot residuals against the predicted values
  plot(residuals ~ predicted, data = dat_fit_1) 
}

8.2 Quadratic Elevation Model

Well only plot the predicted vs.residuals plot here. Since this model has mutliple predictors plotting predictors vs.residuals is more complicated.

{
  dat_fit_3 = data.frame(thrush_sf)
  dat_fit_3$predicted = predict(fit_elev_poly_cen, type="response")
  dat_fit_3$residuals = residuals(fit_elev_poly_cen, type="response")  
  # plot residuals against elevation (the predictor)
  
  plot(residuals ~ elevation, data = dat_fit_3) 
  
  # Plot residuals against the predicted values
  plot(residuals ~ predicted, data = dat_fit_3, pch = 16, cex = 0.1)
}

9 Model Selection

Well use a very simple model selection process: the Akaike Information Criterion (AIC).

The AIC attempts to balance model complexity with model fit. A low AIC value indicates a better model.

{
  AIC(fit_elev_cen, fit_terrain_cen, fit_elev_poly_cen)
}
##                   df      AIC
## fit_elev_cen       2 583.1021
## fit_terrain_cen    4 584.9933
## fit_elev_poly_cen  3 566.5389

The quadratic elevation model seems to be the best because its AIC is the lowest, by around 17.

NOTE: AIC and model selection are complex topics, this is a very simplified selection procedure. In real life you would perform a more thoughtful and thorough model selection procedure.
